# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lin-bus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Electronic systems have become an increasingly large component of the cost of an automobile, from only around 1% of its value in 1950 to around 30% in 2010.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Modern electric cars rely on power electronics for the main propulsion motor control, as well as managing the battery system.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Future autonomous cars will rely on powerful computer systems, an array of sensors, networking, and satellite navigation, all of which will require electronics.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The earliest electronic systems available as factory installations were vacuum tube car radios, starting in the early 1930s.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The development of semiconductors after World War II greatly expanded the use of electronics in automobiles, with solid-state diodes making the automotive alternator the standard after about 1960, and the first transistorized ignition systems appearing in 1963.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The emergence of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology led to the development of modern automotive electronics.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Dawon Kahng summarized in a Bell Labs memo the achievement: E.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Ligenza who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] This led to the development of the power MOSFET by Hitachi in 1969, and the single-chip microprocessor by Federico Faggin, Marcian Hoff, Masatoshi Shima and Stanley Mazor at Intel in 1971.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The development of MOS integrated circuit (MOS IC) chips and microprocessors made a range of automotive applications economically feasible in the 1970s.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] In the early 1970s, the Japanese electronics industry began producing integrated circuits and microcontrollers for the Japanese automobile industry, used for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, dashboard, and engine control.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The Ford EEC (Electronic Engine Control) system, which utilized the Toshiba TLCS-12 PMOS microprocessor, went into mass production in 1975.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] In 1978, the Cadillac Seville featured a "trip computer" based on a 6802 microprocessor.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Electronically-controlled ignition and fuel injection systems allowed automotive designers to achieve vehicles meeting requirements for fuel economy and lower emissions, while still maintaining high levels of performance and convenience for drivers.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Today's automobiles contain a dozen or more processors, in functions such as engine management, transmission control, climate control, antilock braking, passive safety systems, navigation, and other functions.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The power MOSFET and the microcontroller, a type of single-chip microcomputer, led to significant advances in electric vehicle technology.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] MOSFET power converters allowed operation at much higher switching frequencies, made it easier to drive, reduced power losses, and significantly reduced prices, while single-chip microcontrollers could manage all aspects of the drive control and had the capacity for battery management.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used in vehicles such as automobiles, cars, trucks, electric vehicles, and smart cars.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] MOSFETs are used for the electronic control unit (ECU), while the power MOSFET and IGBT are used as the load drivers for automotive loads such as motors, solenoids, ignition coils, relays, heaters and lamps.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] In 2000, the average mid-range passenger vehicle had an estimated $100–200 of power semiconductor content, increasing by a potential 3–5 times for electric and hybrid vehicles.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] As of 2017, the average vehicle has over 50 actuators, typically controlled by power MOSFETs or other power semiconductor devices.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Another important technology that enabled modern highway-capable electric cars is the lithium-ion battery.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] It was invented by John Goodenough, Rachid Yazami and Akira Yoshino in the 1980s, and commercialized by Sony and Asahi Kasei in 1991.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The lithium-ion battery was responsible for the development of electric vehicles capable of long-distance travel, by the 2000s.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] On average, a 2020s car has 50–150 chips, according to Chris Isidore of CNN Business.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] One of the most demanding electronic parts of an automobile is the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Engine controls demand one of the highest real-time deadlines, as the engine itself is a very fast and complex part of the automobile.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Of all the electronics in any car, the computing power of the engine control unit is the highest, typically a 32-bit processor.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] A modern car may have up to 100 ECU's and a commercial vehicle up to 40.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Many more engine parameters are actively monitored and controlled in real-time.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 50 that measure pressure, temperature, flow, engine speed, oxygen level and NOx level plus other parameters at different points within the engine.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] All these sensor signals are sent to the ECU, which has the logic circuits to do the actual controlling.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The ECU output is connected to different actuators for the throttle valve, EGR valve, rack (in VGTs), fuel injector (using a pulse-width modulated signal), dosing injector and more.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] There are about 20 to 30 actuators in all.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] These control the transmission system, mainly the shifting of the gears for better shift comfort and to lower torque interrupt while shifting.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Automatic transmissions use controls for their operation, and also many semi-automatic transmissions having a fully automatic clutch or a semi-auto clutch (declutching only).
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The engine control unit and the transmission control exchange messages, sensor signals and control signals for their operation.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] All of the above systems form an infotainment system.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Developmental methods for these systems vary according to each manufacturer.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Different tools are used for both hardware and software development.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] These are new generation hybrid ECUs that combine the functionalities of multiple ECUs of Infotainment Head Unit, Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS), Instrument Cluster, Rear Camera/Parking Assist, Surround View Systems etc.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] This saves on the cost of electronics as well as mechanical/physical parts like interconnects across ECUs etc.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] There is also a more centralized control so data can be seamlessly exchanged between the systems.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Given the complexity of this hybrid system, a lot more rigor is needed to validate the system for robustness, safety and security.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] For example, if the infotainment system's application which could be running an open-source Android OS is breached, there could be possibility of hackers to take control of the car remotely and potentially misuse it for anti-social activities.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Typically so, usage of a hardware+software enabled hypervisors are used to virtualize and create separate trust and safety zones that are immune to each other's failures or breaches.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Lot of work is happening in this area and potentially will have such systems soon if not already.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] In order to minimize the risk of dangerous failures, safety-related electronic systems have to be developed following the applicable product liability requirements.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Disregard for, or inadequate application of these standards can lead to not only personal injuries, but also severe legal and economic consequences such as product cancellations or recalls.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The IEC 61508 standard, generally applicable to electrical/electronic/programmable safety-related products, is only partially adequate for automotive-development requirements.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Consequently, for the automotive industry, this standard is replaced by the existing ISO 26262, currently released as a Final Draft International Standard (FDIS).
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] ISO/DIS 26262 describes the entire product life-cycle of safety-related electrical/electronic systems for road vehicles.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] It has been published as an international standard in its final version in November 2011.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The implementation of this new standard will result in modifications and various innovations in the automobile electronics development process, as it covers the complete product life-cycle from the concept phase until its decommissioning.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] As more functions of the automobile are connected to short- or long-range networks, cybersecurity of systems against unauthorized modification is required.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] With critical systems such as engine controls, transmission, airbags, and braking connected to internal diagnostic networks, remote access could result in a malicious intruder altering the function of systems or disabling them, possibly causing injuries or fatalities.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Every new interface presents a new "attack surface".
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] The same facility that allows the owner to unlock and start a car from a smartphone app also presents risks due to remote access.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Auto manufacturers may protect the memory of various control microprocessors both to secure them from unauthorized changes and also to ensure only manufacturer-authorized facilities can diagnose or repair the vehicle.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] Systems such as keyless entry rely on cryptographic techniques to ensure "replay" or "man-in-the-middle attacks" attacks cannot record sequences to allow later break-in to the automobile.
[src:lin-bus/automotive-electronics] In 2015 the German general automobile club commissioned an investigation of the vulnerabilities of one manufacturer's electronics system, which could have led to such exploits as unauthorized remote unlocking of the vehicle.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:lin-bus/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:lin-bus/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The need for a cheap serial network arose as the technologies and the facilities implemented in the car grew, while the CAN bus was too expensive to implement for every component in the car.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] European car manufacturers started using different serial communication technologies, which led to compatibility problems.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] In the late 1990s, the LIN Consortium was founded by five automakers (BMW, Volkswagen Group, Audi, Volvo Cars, Mercedes-Benz), with the technologies supplied (networking and hardware expertise) from Volcano Automotive Group and Motorola.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The first fully implemented version of the new LIN specification (LIN version 1.3) was published in November 2002.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] In September 2003, version 2.0 was introduced to expand capabilities and make provisions for additional diagnostics features.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] LIN may be used also over the vehicle's battery power line with a special LIN-over-DC-power-line (DC-LIN) transceiver.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] LIN over DC power line (DC-LIN) was standardized as ISO/AWI 17987-8.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] CAN in Automation has been appointed by the ISO Technical Management Board (TMB) as the Registration Authority for the LIN Supplier ID standardized in the ISO 17987 series.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] LIN is a broadcast serial network comprising 16 nodes (one primary and up to 15 secondary nodes).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] All messages are initiated by the primary node with at most one secondary node replying to a given message identifier.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The primary node can also act as a secondary node by replying to its own messages.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Because all communications are initiated by the primary node it is not necessary to implement a collision detection.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The primary and secondary nodes are typically microcontrollers, but may be implemented in specialized hardware or ASICs in order to save cost, space, or power.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Current uses combine the low-cost efficiency of LIN and simple sensors to create small networks.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] These sub-systems can be connected by a back-bone network (i.e.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The LIN bus is an inexpensive serial communications protocol, which effectively supports remote application within a car's network.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] It is particularly intended for mechatronic nodes in distributed automotive applications, but is equally suited to industrial applications.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] It is intended to complement the existing CAN network leading to hierarchical networks within cars.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] In the late 1990s the Local Interconnect Network (LIN) Consortium was founded by five European automakers, Mentor Graphics (Formerly Volcano Automotive Group) and Freescale (Formerly Motorola, now NXP).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The first fully implemented version of the new LIN specification was published in November 2002 as LIN version 1.3.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] In September 2003 version 2.0 was introduced to expand configuration capabilities and make provisions for significant additional diagnostics features and tool interfaces.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Data is transferred across the bus in fixed-form messages of selectable lengths.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The master task transmits a header that consists of a break signal followed by synchronization and identifier fields.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The slaves respond with a data frame that consists of 2, 4 or 8 data bytes plus 3 bytes of control information.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] **Event-triggered frame.** The purpose of this is to increase the responsiveness of the LIN cluster without assigning too much of the bus bandwidth to the polling of multiple slave nodes with seldom occurring events.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The first data byte of the carried unconditional frame shall be equal to a protected identifier assigned to an event-triggered frame.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] A slave shall reply with an associated unconditional frame only if its data value has changed.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] If none of the slave tasks responds to the header the rest of the frame slot is silent and the header is ignored.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] If more than one slave task responds to the header in the same frame slot a collision will occur, and the master has to resolve the collision by requesting all associated unconditional frames before requesting the event-triggered frame again.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] **Sporadic frame.** This frame is transmitted by the master as required, so a collision cannot occur.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The header of a sporadic frame shall only be sent in its associated frame slot when the master task knows that a signal carried in the frame has been updated.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The publisher of the sporadic frame shall always provide the response to the header.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] **Diagnostic frame.** These always carry diagnostic or configuration data and they always contain eight data bytes.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The identifier is either 60 (0x3C), called master request frame, or 61(0x3D), called slave response frame.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Before generating the header of a diagnostic frame, the master task asks its diagnostic module if it shall be sent or if the bus shall be silent.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The slave tasks publish and subscribe to the response according to their diagnostic module.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] **User-defined frame.** These can carry any kind of information.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] **Reserved frame.** These shall not be used in a LIN 2.0 cluster.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The LIN specification was designed to allow very cheap hardware-nodes being used within a network.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] It is a low-cost, single-wire network based on ISO 9141.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] In today’s car networking topologies, microcontrollers with either UART capability or dedicated LIN hardware are used.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The microcontroller generates all needed LIN data (protocol ...) (partly) by software and is connected to the LIN network via a LIN transceiver (simply speaking, a level shifter with some add-ons).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Working as a LIN node is only part of the possible functionality.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The LIN hardware may include this transceiver and works as a pure LIN node without added functionality.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] As LIN Slave nodes should be as cheap as possible, they may generate their internal clocks by using RC oscillators instead of crystal oscillators (quartz or a ceramic).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] To ensure the baud rate-stability within one LIN frame, the SYNC field within the header is used.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The LIN-Master uses one or more predefined scheduling tables to start the sending and receiving to the LIN bus.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] These scheduling tables contain at least the relative timing, where the message sending is initiated.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] One LIN Frame consists of the two parts: **header** and **response**.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The header is always sent by the LIN Master, while the response is sent by either one dedicated LIN-Slave or the LIN master itself.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Transmitted data within the LIN is transmitted serially as eight bit data bytes with one start bit, one stop-bit, and no parity (break field does not have a start or stop bit).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Bit rates vary within the range of 1 kbit/s to 20 kbit/s.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Data on the bus is divided into recessive (logical HIGH) and dominant (logical LOW).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The time normally is considered by the LIN Masters stable clock source, the smallest entity is one bit time (52 μs @ 19.2 kbit/s).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Two bus states – sleep-mode and active – are used within the LIN protocol.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] While data is on the bus, all LIN-nodes are asked to be in the active state.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] After a specified timeout, the nodes enter sleep mode and will be released back to active state by a WAKEUP frame.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] This frame may be sent by any node requesting activity on the bus, either the LIN Master following its internal schedule, or one of the attached LIN Slaves being activated by its internal software application.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] After all nodes are awakened, the Master continues to schedule the next Identifier.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] There is an Inter Byte Space between the BREAK and SYNC field, one between the SYNC and IDENTIFIER, one between the payload and Checksum and one between every Data byte in the payload.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] If the identifier causes one *physical* LIN slave to send the response, the identifier may be called a Rx-identifier.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] If the *master's slave task* sends data to the bus, it may be called Tx-identifier.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The response is sent by one of the attached LIN slave **tasks** and is divided into data and checksum.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] These methods allow the detection of the position of slave nodes on the LIN bus and allow the assignment of a unique node address (NAD).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Each slave node has to provide two extra pins, one input, D1, and one output, D2.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Each configuration pin Dx (x=1-2) has additional circuitry to aid in the position detection.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] 2.1 The first non addressed SNPD node is selected.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Each slave node needs some additional circuitry compared to the standard LIN circuitry to aid in the position detection.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] At the start of the procedure, none of the SNPD devices have a NAD assigned.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] The autoaddressing routine is performed during the sync field.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] This technique is covered by the patents EP 1490772 B1 and US 7091876.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] LIN is not a full replacement of the CAN bus.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] But the LIN bus is a good alternative wherever low costs are essential and speed/bandwidth is not important.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Typically, it is used within sub-systems that are not critical to vehicle performance or safety - some examples are given below.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] Addressing in LIN is achieved with a NAD (Node ADdress) that is part of the PID (protected identifier).
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] NAD values are on 7bits, so in the range 1 to 127 (0x7F) and it is a composition of supplier ID, function ID and variant ID.
[src:lin-bus/local-interconnect-network] You can obtain a supplier ID by contacting CAN in Automation that is the authority responsible for the assignment of such identifiers.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] In telecommunication and data transmission, **serial communication** is the process of sending data one bit at a time, sequentially, over a communication channel or computer bus.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] This is in contrast to parallel communication, where several bits are sent as a whole, on a link with several parallel channels.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Serial communication is used for all long-haul communication and most computer networks, where the cost of cable and difficulty of synchronization make parallel communication impractical.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The migration from PCI to PCI Express (PCIe) is an example.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Modern high speed serial interfaces such as PCIe send data several bits at a time using modulation/encoding techniques such as PAM4 which groups 2 bits at a time into a single symbol, and several symbols are still sent one at a time.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] This replaces PAM2 or non return to zero (NRZ) which only sends one bit at a time, or in other words one bit per symbol.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The symbols are sent at a speed known as the symbol rate or the baud rate.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Many serial communication systems were originally designed to transfer data over relatively large distances through some sort of data cable.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Practically all long-distance communication transmits data one bit at a time, rather than in parallel, because it reduces the cost of the cable.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The cables that carry this data (other than "the" serial cable) and the computer ports they plug into are usually referred to with a more specific name, to reduce confusion.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Keyboard and mouse cables and ports are almost invariably serial—such as PS/2 port, Apple Desktop Bus and USB.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The cables that carry digital video are also mostly serial—such as coax cable plugged into a HD-SDI port, a webcam plugged into a USB port or FireWire port, Ethernet cable connecting an IP camera to a Power over Ethernet port, FPD-Link, digital telephone lines (ex.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Other such cables and ports, transmitting data one bit at a time, include Serial ATA, Serial SCSI, Ethernet cable plugged into Ethernet ports, the Display Data Channel using previously reserved pins of the VGA connector or the DVI port or the HDMI port.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Many communication systems were generally designed to connect two integrated circuits on the same printed circuit board, connected by signal traces on that board (rather than external cables).
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Integrated circuits are more expensive when they have more pins.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] To reduce the number of pins in a package, many ICs use a serial bus to transfer data when speed is not important.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Some examples of such low-cost lower-speed serial buses include RS-232, DALI, SPI, CAN bus, I²C, UNI/O, and 1-Wire.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Higher-speed serial buses include USB, SATA and PCI Express.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The communication links, across which computers (or parts of computers) talk to one another, may be either serial or parallel.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] A parallel link transmits several streams of data simultaneously along multiple channels (e.g., wires, printed circuit tracks, or optical fibers); whereas, a serial link transmits only a single stream of data.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The rationale for parallel communication was the added benefit of having Direct Memory Access to the 8-bit or 16-bit registry addresses at a time when mapping direct data lanes was more convenient and faster than synchronizing data serially.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Although a serial link may seem inferior to a parallel one, since it can transmit less data per clock cycle, it is often the case that serial links can be clocked considerably faster than parallel links in order to achieve a higher data rate.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] The transition from parallel to serial buses was allowed by Moore's law which allowed for the incorporation of SerDes in integrated circuits.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] An electrical serial link only requires a pair of wires, whereas a parallel link requires several.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Thus serial links can save on costs (also known as the Bill of Materials).
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Differential signalling uses length-matched wires or conductors and are used in high speed serial links.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Length-matching is easier to perform on serial links as they require fewer conductors.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] In many cases, serial is cheaper to implement than parallel.
[src:lin-bus/serial-communication] Many ICs have serial interfaces, as opposed to parallel ones, so that they have fewer pins and are therefore less expensive.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In engineering, **master–slave** is a relationship between two systems in which one controls the other.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In some cases, one master controls just one slave system, but in others, there are multiple slave systems controlled by the same master.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Sometimes the master is a different kind of system than the slave, but sometimes there are multiple similar systems and one of them is designated the master in order to centralize external (i.e., user) control of the collection.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Due to it being prone to being associated with slavery, the terminology is a subject of controversy and has been replaced with alternative terms in some cases.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In photography, secondary, or slave, flash units are connected to a master unit to provide synchronized lighting.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Parallel audio duplication often entails multiple recording with devices (i.e., for cassette tape or compact disc) linked together so that operating the controls of a master device triggers the same commands on slave devices.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Railway locomotives operating in the same train (for example, to pull a load too heavy for a single locomotive) may be configured for master–slave operation with all but one of the locomotives controlled from the first.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In a hydraulic system, a master cylinder is a control device that converts force into hydraulic pressure that drives movement in a slave cylinder at the other end of the hydraulic line.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] A common application is a vehicle brake system.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] A master clock provides time signals used to synchronize one or more slave clocks as part of a clock network.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] A slave clock receives and displays the time from a master, though it may be able to keep time itself if the master is not working.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Computer bus protocols often use a master-slave relationship.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] For instance, a USB host manages access to the USB bus shared by any number of USB devices.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] A serial peripheral interface (SPI) bus typically has a single master controlling multiple slaves.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] I2C and I3C may even have multiple masters on a bus.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Modbus also uses a master device to initiate connection requests to slave devices.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] An edge-triggered flip-flop can be created by arranging two gated latches in a master–slave configuration.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] It is so named because the master latch controls the slave latch's value and forces the slave latch to hold its value, as the slave latch always copies its new value from the master latch.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In database replication, the master database is the authoritative source.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The slave or replica database is controlled by the master database, which repeats its update commands (for example by way of event log) to the slave.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Some databases implement so called *multi-master replication*, where a mix of writeable master nodes and readable nodes is used.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] These databases are used in scenarios where performance is an acceptable tradeoff for ACID properties, for example, non-mission-critical data, like suggesting similar purchases.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The term *master* is used in some technology contexts that do not refer to a relationship of control.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] *Master* may be used to mean a copy that has more significance than other copies, in which case the term is an absolute concept, not a relationship.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Sometimes the term *master–slave* is used in contexts that do not imply a controlling relationship.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In source code management *master* may refer to the trunk.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In disk imaging, the gold master is the version that will be released to manufacturing for duplication.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] A Parallel ATA (aka IDE) hard drive interface supports two hard drives on a cable, which are designated *master* and *slave*.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The distinction is required by the interface even though neither drive has control or priority over the other.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The *master–slave* terminology was first used in 1904.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The terminology was used in 1988 for RFC 1059 and in 1997 for RFC 2136, related to the domain name system.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Said hydraulic brakes for the automotive industry were patented in 1917 by Malcolm Loughead.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The term *slave cylinder* was used in other patent applications, including one by Robert Esnault-Pelterie, published in 1919.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Media analytics company Global Language Monitor placed *master/slave* first in their annual list of politically charged language for 2004.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The Black Lives Matter movement in the United States sparked renewed discussion, and terminology changes occurred in 2020.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Some argued, however, that terminology changes were superficial or performative activism.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In 2003, after receiving a discrimination complaint from a county employee, the County of Los Angeles in California asked that manufacturers, suppliers and contractors stop using *master* and *slave* terminology on products.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Following complaints, the County of Los Angeles issued a statement saying that the decision was "nothing more than a request".
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In 2018, after a heated debate, developers of Python replaced the term.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Depending on context, Python switched to *main*, *parent*, or *server* (in place of *master*), and *worker*, *child*, or *helper* (in place of *slave*).
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] The Linux kernel adopted a similar policy to use more specific terms in new code and documentation.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In July 2018, Google's developer style guide was updated to include avoiding the term *master* in software documentation, especially in combination with *slave.* Instead, the guide recommends terms – when in combination – such as *primary/secondary* and *original/replica*.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] Many individual variants of master and slave are given.
[src:lin-bus/slave-technology] In 2020, GitHub renamed the default *master* git branch to *main*.
